  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-absolute-primary",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary absolute hemolysis index validation — FDA generic centrifugal pump, 5 operating points",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-hemolysis",
      "description": "This validation result captures the comparison of CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values against in-vitro measurements obtained at the FDA laboratory using the generic centrifugal blood pump test rig. Five operating conditions were evaluated spanning 2–6 L/min flow rate and 2500–4500 RPM impeller speed. The CFD solver employed a power-law hemolysis damage accumulation model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger coefficients) integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories seeded at the inlet. Mesh density was 14.2 million polyhedral cells confirmed by a three-level GCI study showing less than 1.8% discretization uncertainty on NIH. Monte Carlo sampling over six uncertain input parameters (fluid viscosity, pump geometry tolerances, inlet velocity profile, turbulence intensity, hemolysis model coefficients α and β) was executed with 2000 LHS samples per operating point. The 95th-percentile NIH prediction remained below the absolute clinical threshold of 0.01 g/100 L at all five operating points. Mean NIH bias relative to experimental measurements was −4.3% (CFD under-predicts), within the combined experimental and model-form uncertainty band. Validation comparison metric used was the ASME V&V 20 area metric with E/D ratio reported per operating point. All five E/D ratios fell within [0.72, 1.18], satisfying the acceptance criterion of E/D ∈ [0.5, 2.0] for this credibility level. The experimental campaign was conducted under GLP-equivalent conditions with triplicate measurements per operating point; coefficient of variation on experimental NIH was below 8% across all conditions. Full uncertainty budget including numerical, model-form, and experimental contributions is documented in the UQ report appended to the submission dossier."
    },
